{{about||the United States Army's African operations in World War II|Mediterranean Theater of Operations|WWI|African theatre of World War I}}
The '''African Theatre''' was an [[African-American]] acting [[wiktionary:troupe|troupe]] in [[New York City]] established by [[William Henry Brown (playwright)|William Henry Brown]] in the 1820s. The troupe performed plays by [[Shakespeare]] and plays written by Brown, several of which were anti-colonization and [[Abolitionism in the United States|anti-slavery]]. Its leading actor was James Hewlett.<ref name="review">{{cite journal |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+Documentary+History+of+the+African+Theater.-a067413419 |title=A Documentary History of the African Theater, by George A. Thompson, Jr.&nbsp;– book review |last=Hill |first=Errol |authorlink=Errol Hill |journal=[[African American Review]] |date=Fall 2000 |accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref>

The troupe faced violence, including attacks by thugs hired by the [[Park Theatre (Manhattan)|Park Theatre]].<ref name="review"/>  Little is known of the participants as a result of the destruction of the records of the troupe.

