'''Muhammad ibn Iyas''' (b. June 1448; d. after November 1522), is one of the most important Egyptian historians.<ref>[http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Pub/magazin/summer2006/110231000000000010.htm SIS.gov.eg] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211022051/http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Pub/magazin/summer2006/110231000000000010.htm |date=2008-12-11 }}{{Citation not found}}</ref>{{Citation not found}} He was an eyewitness to the historical event of the Ottoman invasion of [[Egypt]]. 

Of [[Circassians| circassian]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=W.M.|first1=Brinner,|title=Ibn Iyās|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/ibn-iyas-SIM_3225?s.num=0&s.f.s2_parent=s.f.book.encyclopaedia-of-islam-2&s.q=Ibn+Iy%C4%81s|language=en}}</ref> origin, He was one of the [[Memluk]]s and was entitled Bada'I al-Zuhur fi Waqa'I al-Duhur.

His quotes have been used in many references like his say about [[Al-Nasir Muhammad]]:  " His name was mentioned everywhere like no other king's name. All the kings wrote to him, sent  gifts to him and feared him. The whole of Egypt was in his grasp ".

==Work==
Ibn Iyas was the author of a 6-volume history of Egypt, totalling over 3,000 pages.,<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1310/is_1989_April/ai_7655987 Findarticles.com] {{Citation not found}}</ref>{{Citation not found}} This is entitled "Badai Alzuhur Fi Wakayi Alduhur" <ref>[[Ibn Iyas]] , Badai Alzuhur Fi Wakayi Alduhur , abridged and edited by Dr. M. Aljayar, Almisriya Lilkitab, Cairo 2007, {{ISBN|977-419-623-6}} , p.91 {{Citation not found}}</ref>{{Citation not found}}

